responses.text:
Below is a single, self-contained HTML file you can save (e.g., race-demo.html) and open in a browser. It shows two counters side-by-side: the left one is buggy and exhibits a race condition when you click rapidly; the right one shows a corrected implementation. Each counter uses asynchronous updates (setTimeout) to simulate a delayed read-modify-write on a shared variable. Explanations are included in the page and beneath each counter.

Save the contents as a .html file and open it in a browser.

```html
<!doctype html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="utf-8" />
  <title>Race Condition Demo: Buggy vs Fixed Counter</title>
  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width,initial-scale=1" />
  <style>
    body {
      font-family: system-ui, -apple-system, "Segoe UI", Roboto, "Helvetica Neue", Arial;
      margin: 24px;
      background: #f7f9fc;
      color: #0b1220;
    }
    h1 { margin-top: 0; }
    .container {
      display: flex;
      gap: 20px;
      align-items: flex-start;
      flex-wrap: wrap;
    }
    .panel {
      background: white;
      border: 1px solid #e1e6ef;
      border-radius: 8px;
      padding: 16px;
      width: 420px;
      box-shadow: 0 6px 18px rgba(14,30,37,0.06);
    }
    .panel h2 { margin: 0 0 6px 0; font-size: 18px; }
    .desc { color: #334155; font-size: 13px; margin-bottom: 12px; line-height: 1.4; }
    .count-box {
      display: flex;
      gap: 10px;
      align-items: center;
      margin-bottom: 12px;
    }
    .display {
      width: 120px;
      height: 60px;
      border-radius: 8px;
      background: linear-gradient(180deg,#ffffff,#f5f8ff);
      border: 1px solid #e6eefc;
      display: flex;
      align-items: center;
      justify-content: center;
      font-size: 28px;
      font-weight: 700;
      color: #0b1220;
      box-shadow: inset 0 -6px 18px rgba(14,30,37,0.02);
    }
    button {
      padding: 10px 14px;
      border-radius: 8px;
      border: 1px solid #cbd8ff;
      background: linear-gradient(180deg,#4f7cff,#3961db);
      color: white;
      font-weight: 600;
      cursor: pointer;
    }
    button:active { transform: translateY(1px); }
    .log {
      height: 220px;
      overflow: auto;
      font-family: monospace;
      background: #0f1724;
      color: #e6eefc;
      padding: 10px;
      border-radius: 6px;
      font-size: 12px;
      line-height: 1.35;
    }
    .controls { margin-bottom: 8px; display:flex; gap:8px; align-items:center; }
    .small { font-size: 12px; color: #475569; }
    .explain { margin-top: 10px; font-size: 13px; color: #0b1220; background:#fcfcff; border-left:4px solid #cfe0ff; padding:10px; border-radius:6px; }
    .fixed-note { color:#065f46; font-weight:600; }
    .bug-note { color:#7f1d1d; font-weight:600; }
    footer { margin-top: 18px; color:#475569; font-size:13px; }
    .speed-range { width: 160px; }
    .row { display:flex; gap:8px; align-items:center; margin-bottom:8px; }
    .muted { color: #64748b; font-size: 13px; }
  </style>
</head>
<body>
  <h1>Race Condition Demo: Buggy vs Fixed Counter</h1>
  <p class="muted">Click the "Increment" buttons rapidly. Each increment uses an asynchronous delayed update (setTimeout) that reads the shared counter, waits, then writes the new value. The left implementation is intentionally buggy and will sometimes lose increments when clicks overlap. The right implementation uses a safe pattern to avoid the race. Adjust the artificial delay to make the race more or less likely.</p>

  <div style="display:flex; gap:12px; align-items:center; margin-bottom:12px;">
    <label class="small">Artificial delay (ms): <span id="delayVal">120</span></label>
    <input id="delay" class="speed-range" type="range" min="10" max="800" value="120" />
    <div style="flex:1"></div>
    <div class="small">Rapid clicks create overlapping async updates that demonstrate the race.</div>
  </div>

  <div class="container">
    <!-- Buggy panel -->
    <div class="panel" id="buggyPanel">
      <h2>Buggy Version (race occurs)</h2>
      <div class="desc">This version reads the shared counter, waits asynchronously, then writes the incremented value back. If you click fast, multiple timeouts read the same old value before previous writes complete, so some increments get lost.</div>

      <div class="count-box">
        <div class="display" id="buggyDisplay">0</div>
        <div>
          <div class="row">
            <button id="buggyInc">Increment</button>
            <button id="buggyReset">Reset</button>
          </div>
          <div class="small">Shared variable: <code>sharedCount</code></div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="small" style="margin-bottom:6px;">Operation log (newest first):</div>
      <div class="log" id="buggyLog"></div>

      <div class="explain">
        <div><span class="bug-note">Why the race happens:</span> Each click handler does:
          1) read sharedCount,
          2) schedule a delayed function (setTimeout),
          3) inside the delayed function, compute readValue + 1 and write back to sharedCount.
        If two handlers read the same value before either delayed function writes, they both compute the same result and one write overwrites the other — one increment is lost.</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Fixed panel -->
    <div class="panel" id="fixedPanel">
      <h2>Fixed Version (atomic update)</h2>
      <div class="desc">This version avoids the race by performing the update in one place that serializes modifications (acts like an atomic update): the increment request is queued and applied synchronously when the timeout fires, but each queued update uses the then-current shared value rather than a stale read. Two common fixes are: 1) holding the increment logic in a single central updater (apply-once), or 2) using a functional update that uses the latest value at write time. Here we implement a small update queue which ensures each increment uses the most recent value when applied.</div>

      <div class="count-box">
        <div class="display" id="fixedDisplay">0</div>
        <div>
          <div class="row">
            <button id="fixedInc">Increment</button>
            <button id="fixedReset">Reset</button>
          </div>
          <div class="small">Shared variable: <code>safeSharedCount</code></div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="small" style="margin-bottom:6px;">Operation log (newest first):</div>
      <div class="log" id="fixedLog"></div>

      <div class="explain">
        <div><span class="fixed-note">How the fix works:</span> Instead of each click capturing a stale read, the click creates a "task" that, when its timeout fires, requests "apply an increment now." The central updater applies that increment atomically using the then-current count. Even if multiple timeouts fire at once, each applies on top of the latest value, so no increments are lost.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <footer>
    Tip: Increase the delay and click rapidly to make the buggy counter lose more increments. The logs show each read/write to make the race visible.
  </footer>

  <script>
    // Shared settings
    const delayInput = document.getElementById('delay');
    const delayVal = document.getElementById('delayVal');
    delayVal.textContent = delayInput.value;
    delayInput.addEventListener('input', () => { delayVal.textContent = delayInput.value; });

    // -----------------------------
    // Buggy implementation
    // -----------------------------
    (function(){
      let sharedCount = 0; // the shared variable that both reading and writing operations use
      const display = document.getElementById('buggyDisplay');
      const logEl = document.getElementById('buggyLog');

      function log(msg) {
        const time = new Date().toLocaleTimeString();
        logEl.textContent = `[${time}] ${msg}\n` + logEl.textContent;
      }

      document.getElementById('buggyInc').addEventListener('click', () => {
        // read
        const readValue = sharedCount;
        log(`read -> ${readValue} (captured by click)`);
        // schedule async write after artificial delay
        const d = Number(delayInput.value);
        setTimeout(() => {
          // compute and write using the captured readValue
          const newVal = readValue + 1;
          sharedCount = newVal; // write back
          display.textContent = sharedCount;
          log(`delayed write -> wrote ${newVal} (based on captured ${readValue})`);
        }, d);
      });

      document.getElementById('buggyReset').addEventListener('click', () => {
        sharedCount = 0;
        display.textContent = 0;
        log('RESET -> 0');
      });
    })();

    // -----------------------------
    // Fixed implementation (queue + apply using current value)
    // -----------------------------
    (function(){
      let safeSharedCount = 0;
      const display = document.getElementById('fixedDisplay');
      const logEl = document.getElementById('fixedLog');

      function log(msg) {
        const time = new Date().toLocaleTimeString();
        logEl.textContent = `[${time}] ${msg}\n` + logEl.textContent;
      }

      // Approach: each click enqueues a "task" that will request an increment when its timeout fires.
      // When the timeout fires, instead of using a stale captured value, the task calls a central applyIncrement()
      // that reads the current safeSharedCount and updates it. This ensures increments are applied sequentially
      // using the latest value.
      function applyIncrement(sourceTag) {
        const before = safeSharedCount;
        const after = before + 1;
        safeSharedCount = after;
        display.textContent = safeSharedCount;
        log(`${sourceTag}: applied +1 -> ${before} -> ${after}`);
      }

      document.getElementById('fixedInc').addEventListener('click', () => {
        // schedule a task that, when its timeout fires, asks to apply an increment now.
        log('click -> queued increment request');
        const d = Number(delayInput.value);
        setTimeout(() => {
          // When this runs, it uses the current safeSharedCount inside applyIncrement(),
          // so even if other increments applied earlier, this one will build on the latest.
          applyIncrement('delayed task');
        }, d);
      });

      document.getElementById('fixedReset').addEventListener('click', () => {
        safeSharedCount = 0;
        display.textContent = 0;
        log('RESET -> 0');
      });
    })();

    // Additional note to help reproduce:
    // - For the buggy version, each delayed callback uses the captured 'readValue', which may be stale.
    // - For the fixed version, each delayed callback does not use a previously captured value;
    //   instead it instructs the central updater to increment the current value when the timeout runs.
  </script>
</body>
</html>
```

How to observe the bug
- Set the delay to a moderate value (100–400 ms), then click the Buggy "Increment" button rapidly (multiple clicks within a few hundred ms). Watch the buggy counter or its log: you will see several delayed writes that were all based on the same captured readValue, causing later writes to overwrite earlier increments and resulting in a displayed count smaller than the number of clicks.
- The Fixed counter never loses increments because each delayed task applies its increment against the then-current value.

If you'd like, I can:
- Provide an alternate fixed approach using a mutex/lock, or using Promise-based serial execution.
- Modify the demo to show visual overlays for each pending timeout and their captured values.

Below is a single self-contained HTML file you can save (e.g., as race-demo.html) and open in a browser. It presents two counters side-by-side:

- "Buggy counter" — intentionally vulnerable to a race condition: each click triggers an asynchronous update that reads the shared count variable, waits (setTimeout with random delay) and then writes back count + 1. If multiple handlers run concurrently they can read the same initial value and overwrite each other, producing missed increments.
- "Fixed counter" — uses a simple queuing/locking approach: every update enqueues its increment and a single runner processes updates sequentially (or alternatively uses a compare-and-set loop). This ensures increments are applied one-by-one and no writes are lost.

The page also contains visible explanation text and buttons you can click rapidly to reproduce the incorrect behavior.

Save the text below into a file and open it in a modern browser.

```html
<!doctype html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
<meta charset="utf-8"/>
<meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width,initial-scale=1"/>
<title>Race Condition Demo: Buggy vs Fixed Counter</title>
<style>
  body { font-family: system-ui, -apple-system, "Segoe UI", Roboto, "Helvetica Neue", Arial; padding: 20px; background: #f5f7fb; color: #111; }
  h1 { margin-top: 0; }
  .container { display: flex; gap: 20px; align-items: flex-start; }
  .card { background: white; border-radius: 8px; box-shadow: 0 6px 18px rgba(20,30,70,0.07); padding: 16px; width: 420px; }
  .title { font-weight: 700; margin-bottom: 8px; display:flex; justify-content:space-between; align-items:center; }
  .count { font-size: 48px; font-weight: 700; margin: 8px 0; text-align:center; }
  .controls { display:flex; gap:8px; justify-content:center; margin-top: 8px; }
  button { padding: 8px 12px; border-radius:6px; border: 1px solid #c9d4ee; background: linear-gradient(#fff,#f6f9ff); cursor:pointer; }
  button:active { transform: translateY(1px); }
  .explain { margin-top: 12px; background:#f0f4ff; border:1px solid #d6e2ff; padding:10px; border-radius:6px; font-size:14px; color:#07204a; }
  .log { margin-top:10px; max-height:160px; overflow:auto; font-family: monospace; font-size:12px; background:#0b1220; color:#cfe8ff; padding:8px; border-radius:6px; }
  .footer { margin-top:16px; font-size:13px; color:#334155; }
  .label { font-size:13px; color:#334155; text-align:center; }
  .speed { text-align:center; margin-top:8px; }
  input[type=range] { width:100%; }
  .small { font-size:12px; color:#556; }
</style>
</head>
<body>
  <h1>Race condition demo: Buggy vs Fixed counter</h1>
  <p class="small">Click the "Increment" buttons rapidly (or hold the mouse) to trigger asynchronous overlapping updates. The buggy version can lose increments. The fixed version serializes updates so the count never falls behind.</p>

  <div class="container">
    <div class="card" id="buggyCard">
      <div class="title">
        <div>Buggy counter (race-prone)</div>
        <div class="label">Shared state: single number</div>
      </div>

      <div style="display:flex; gap:12px; align-items:center;">
        <div style="flex:1">
          <div class="count" id="buggyDisplay">0</div>
          <div class="controls">
            <button id="buggyInc">Increment</button>
            <button id="buggySpam">Start Rapid Click</button>
            <button id="buggyStop">Stop</button>
          </div>
          <div class="speed">
            Delay multiplier: <input id="buggyDelay" type="range" min="0" max="2000" step="50" value="600">
            <div class="small">Adds random delay up to chosen ms to simulate async work.</div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="explain" id="buggyExplain">
        How it works (buggy): on click we read the current shared count, wait asynchronously (random delay),
        then write back (readValue + 1). If two clicks read the same value before either writes, one write overwrites the other and a count increment is lost.
      </div>

      <div class="log" id="buggyLog" aria-live="polite"></div>
    </div>

    <div class="card" id="fixedCard">
      <div class="title">
        <div>Fixed counter (sequential)</div>
        <div class="label">Applies updates one at a time</div>
      </div>

      <div style="display:flex; gap:12px; align-items:center;">
        <div style="flex:1">
          <div class="count" id="fixedDisplay">0</div>
          <div class="controls">
            <button id="fixedInc">Increment</button>
            <button id="fixedSpam">Start Rapid Click</button>
            <button id="fixedStop">Stop</button>
          </div>
          <div class="speed">
            Delay multiplier: <input id="fixedDelay" type="range" min="0" max="2000" step="50" value="600">
            <div class="small">Same asynchronous delay, but updates are queued and processed sequentially.</div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="explain" id="fixedExplain">
        Fix approach: queue each increment request and process them one-by-one. Each queued job reads the current value only when it runs, ensuring no concurrent reads/writes can conflict.
      </div>

      <div class="log" id="fixedLog" aria-live="polite"></div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="footer">
    Notes:
    <ul>
      <li>Rapidly click both Increment buttons and watch logs. The buggy counter may skip increments when multiple async handlers overlap.</li>
      <li>The fixed counter sacrifices some concurrency for correctness by serializing updates; other techniques include optimistic compare-and-swap or using atomic operations where available.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

<script>
(function(){
  // Utility: random delay up to max ms
  function randDelay(max) {
    return Math.floor(Math.random() * (Number(max) || 0));
  }

  // ---------- Buggy counter implementation ----------
  const buggyState = { count: 0 };
  const buggyDisplay = document.getElementById('buggyDisplay');
  const buggyLog = document.getElementById('buggyLog');
  const buggyDelayRange = document.getElementById('buggyDelay');

  function buggyLogLine(text) {
    const el = document.createElement('div');
    el.textContent = text;
    buggyLog.appendChild(el);
    // keep log length reasonable
    if (buggyLog.childElementCount > 200) buggyLog.removeChild(buggyLog.firstChild);
    buggyLog.scrollTop = buggyLog.scrollHeight;
  }

  function buggyAsyncIncrement(callerId) {
    // read shared value immediately
    const readValue = buggyState.count;
    const delay = randDelay(buggyDelayRange.value) + 20; // ensure some delay
    buggyLogLine(`[${callerId}] READ ${readValue} -> scheduling write +1 after ${delay}ms`);
    // asynchronous work (e.g., network, timeout)
    setTimeout(() => {
      const newValue = readValue + 1;
      buggyLogLine(`[${callerId}] WRITING ${newValue} (overwriting current ${buggyState.count})`);
      buggyState.count = newValue; // potential overwrite of concurrent updates
      buggyDisplay.textContent = buggyState.count;
    }, delay);
  }

  document.getElementById('buggyInc').addEventListener('click', () => {
    const id = Math.random().toString(36).slice(2,7);
    buggyAsyncIncrement(id);
  });

  // rapid click helper
  let buggySpamTimer = null;
  document.getElementById('buggySpam').addEventListener('click', () => {
    if (buggySpamTimer) return;
    buggyLogLine('--- START rapid clicks ---');
    buggySpamTimer = setInterval(() => {
      document.getElementById('buggyInc').click();
    }, 40); // click ~25 times per second
  });
  document.getElementById('buggyStop').addEventListener('click', () => {
    if (buggySpamTimer) {
      clearInterval(buggySpamTimer); buggySpamTimer = null;
      buggyLogLine('--- STOP rapid clicks ---');
    }
  });

  // ---------- Fixed counter implementation (queue) ----------
  const fixedState = { count: 0 };
  const fixedDisplay = document.getElementById('fixedDisplay');
  const fixedLog = document.getElementById('fixedLog');
  const fixedDelayRange = document.getElementById('fixedDelay');

  function fixedLogLine(text) {
    const el = document.createElement('div');
    el.textContent = text;
    fixedLog.appendChild(el);
    if (fixedLog.childElementCount > 200) fixedLog.removeChild(fixedLog.firstChild);
    fixedLog.scrollTop = fixedLog.scrollHeight;
  }

  // A simple queue that serializes update tasks.
  const fixedQueue = {
    tasks: [],
    running: false,
    enqueue(task) {
      this.tasks.push(task);
      if (!this.running) this.runNext();
    },
    runNext() {
      if (this.tasks.length === 0) {
        this.running = false;
        return;
      }
      this.running = true;
      const task = this.tasks.shift();
      // run task (task returns a Promise)
      task().then(() => {
        // next
        this.runNext();
      }).catch((err) => {
        fixedLogLine('Task error: ' + String(err));
        this.runNext();
      });
    }
  };

  // Each increment enqueues a job. The job reads current value when it runs,
  // performs async delay, then writes incremented value.
  function fixedEnqueueIncrement(callerId) {
    fixedQueue.enqueue(() => {
      // This function returns a Promise
      return new Promise((resolve) => {
        const delay = randDelay(fixedDelayRange.value) + 20;
        fixedLogLine(`[${callerId}] QUEUED -> will run now, read current ${fixedState.count}, wait ${delay}ms, then write +1`);
        // read current only when job executes (we are single-threaded here)
        const readValue = fixedState.count;
        setTimeout(() => {
          const newValue = readValue + 1;
          fixedLogLine(`[${callerId}] WRITING ${newValue} (current was ${fixedState.count})`);
          fixedState.count = newValue;
          fixedDisplay.textContent = fixedState.count;
          resolve();
        }, delay);
      });
    });
  }

  document.getElementById('fixedInc').addEventListener('click', () => {
    const id = Math.random().toString(36).slice(2,7);
    fixedEnqueueIncrement(id);
  });

  // rapid click helper for fixed
  let fixedSpamTimer = null;
  document.getElementById('fixedSpam').addEventListener('click', () => {
    if (fixedSpamTimer) return;
    fixedLogLine('--- START rapid clicks ---');
    fixedSpamTimer = setInterval(() => {
      document.getElementById('fixedInc').click();
    }, 40);
  });
  document.getElementById('fixedStop').addEventListener('click', () => {
    if (fixedSpamTimer) {
      clearInterval(fixedSpamTimer); fixedSpamTimer = null;
      fixedLogLine('--- STOP rapid clicks ---');
    }
  });

  // Optional: let user reset both counters by double-clicking the display.
  function addReset(displayEl, stateObj, logFunc) {
    displayEl.addEventListener('dblclick', () => {
      stateObj.count = 0;
      displayEl.textContent = '0';
      logFunc('RESET to 0');
    });
  }
  addReset(buggyDisplay, buggyState, buggyLogLine);
  addReset(fixedDisplay, fixedState, fixedLogLine);

  // Seed logs with instructions
  buggyLogLine('Tip: double-click the display to reset to 0. Use Start Rapid Click to reproduce race.');
  fixedLogLine('Tip: double-click the display to reset to 0. Uses a queue to serialize updates.');

})();
</script>
</body>
</html>
```

Short explanation (also shown on the page):
- Why the race occurs: in the buggy version each click handler immediately reads the shared count, then schedules an asynchronous write of readValue + 1 later. If two handlers read the same original value before either write happens, both will write the same newValue, so one increment is lost. The fixed version avoids this by queuing updates so a job reads the latest value only when it's its turn, ensuring every request results in a distinct applied increment.

Below is a single self-contained HTML file you can save (e.g., as race-condition-demo.html) and open in a browser. It contains two counter widgets side-by-side:

- Left: a deliberately buggy implementation that simulates a race condition by performing an asynchronous "read-modify-write" using setTimeout. Rapid clicks cause overlapping operations to read stale values and produce incorrect visible counts.
- Right: a corrected implementation that avoids the race by serializing updates (using a simple operation queue) so each update runs after the previous finishes, preserving correctness even when clicks overlap.

The page also shows an explanation of why the race happens and a small visual log so you can watch operations interleave.

Save the content below as a file and open it in your browser.

<!doctype html>
<html>
<head>
  <meta charset="utf-8">
  <title>Race Condition Demo: Counter (Buggy vs Fixed)</title>
  <style>
    body { font-family: system-ui, -apple-system, Segoe UI, Roboto, "Helvetica Neue", Arial; margin: 24px; color: #111; }
    h1 { margin-bottom: 6px; }
    .wrap { display:flex; gap:24px; align-items:flex-start; }
    .panel {
      width: 420px;
      border: 1px solid #ddd;
      border-radius: 8px;
      padding: 12px;
      box-shadow: 0 2px 6px rgba(0,0,0,0.04);
    }
    .title { font-weight:600; margin-bottom:8px; }
    .count {
      font-size: 48px;
      font-weight: 700;
      margin: 10px 0;
      text-align:center;
    }
    button { display:block; margin: 8px auto; padding: 10px 14px; font-size:16px; cursor:pointer; }
    .log {
      height: 180px; overflow:auto; background:#f9f9f9; border-radius:6px; padding:8px; font-family: monospace; font-size:12px; border:1px solid #eee;
    }
    .controls { text-align:center; margin-top:8px; }
    .explain {
      margin-top:12px;
      font-size:13px;
      line-height:1.35;
      background:#fffef6; border:1px solid #fff0b3; padding:10px; border-radius:6px;
    }
    .badge { font-size:11px; color:#666; background:#f0f0f0; padding:4px 8px; border-radius:999px; border:1px solid #e0e0e0; }
    .row { display:flex; justify-content:space-between; align-items:center; gap:10px; }
    .small { font-size:12px; color:#555; }
    .delay-input { width:64px; }
  </style>
</head>
<body>
  <h1>Race Condition Demo: Counter (Buggy vs Fixed)</h1>
  <div class="small">Click rapidly on either "Increment" button. Each click triggers an asynchronous read/modify/write that takes a little time (simulated). The left counter is intentionally buggy; the right counter serializes updates to avoid the race.</div>

  <div style="height:12px;"></div>

  <div class="wrap">
    <div class="panel" id="bug-panel">
      <div class="title">Buggy Counter (race-prone)</div>
      <div class="row">
        <div class="badge">Shared state: count</div>
        <div class="small">Simulated async delay: <input id="bug-delay" class="delay-input" type="number" value="120" min="0"> ms</div>
      </div>
      <div class="count" id="bug-count">0</div>
      <div class="controls">
        <button id="bug-inc">Increment</button>
        <button id="bug-reset">Reset</button>
      </div>
      <div style="height:8px;"></div>
      <div class="small"><strong>Operation log (most recent first)</strong></div>
      <div class="log" id="bug-log"></div>
      <div class="explain" id="bug-explain">
        This version does: read current count -> wait (async) -> write count+1.
