  <style>
    body { font-family: system-ui, -apple-system, "Segoe UI", Roboto, Arial; padding: 16px; }
    .columns { display:flex; gap:20px; align-items:flex-start; }
    .panel { border:1px solid #ccc; padding:12px; width: 48%; box-sizing: border-box; border-radius:6px; }
    h2 { margin:4px 0 12px; font-size:16px; }
    .counter { font-size:32px; margin:8px 0; font-weight:600; }
    button { padding:8px 12px; font-size:14px; }
    .log { height:160px; overflow:auto; background:#fafafa; border:1px solid #eee; margin-top:8px; padding:6px; font-family:monospace; font-size:12px; }
    .note { font-size:13px; color:#444; margin-top:8px; }
  </style>
</head>
<body>
  <h1>Race Condition Demo: Buggy vs Fixed Counter</h1>
  <p>Rapidly click both "Increment" buttons. Each click schedules an asynchronous update with a small random delay (setTimeout). The buggy side reads-modifies-writes shared state without coordination and can lose increments. The fixed side uses a simple async mutex to serialize updates.</p>

  <div class="columns">
    <div class="panel" id="buggyPanel">
      <h2>Buggy Counter (loses increments)</h2>
      <div>Shared state value: <span class="counter" id="buggyValue">0</span></div>
      <button id="buggyInc">Increment</button>
      <button id="buggyRapid">Rapid clicks (100ms for 2s)</button>
      <div class="note">Behavior: each click schedules a delayed callback that reads current value, waits, then writes value+1. When many callbacks interleave, increments can be lost.</div>
      <div class="log" id="buggyLog"></div>
    </div>

    <div class="panel" id="fixedPanel">
      <h2>Fixed Counter (serializes updates with async lock)</h2>
      <div>Shared state value: <span class="counter" id="fixedValue">0</span></div>
      <button id="fixedInc">Increment</button>
      <button id="fixedRapid">Rapid clicks (100ms for 2s)</button>
      <div class="note">Behavior: uses a mutex so each asynchronous update completes (reads-modifies-writes) before the next starts.</div>
      <div class="log" id="fixedLog"></div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <script>
  // Utility: append to logs (keeps size reasonable)
  function appendLog(el, msg) {
    const line = document.createElement('div');
    line.textContent = msg;
    el.appendChild(line);
    // keep last 200 lines
    while (el.childNodes.length > 200) el.removeChild(el.firstChild);
    el.scrollTop = el.scrollHeight;
  }

  // Random delay to increase chance of interleaving (20-150ms)
  function randomDelay() {
    return 20 + Math.floor(Math.random()*130);
  }

  // ---- Buggy version ----
  (function(){
    let state = { value: 0 }; // shared state object
    const valueEl = document.getElementById('buggyValue');
    const logEl = document.getElementById('buggyLog');
    function render() { valueEl.textContent = String(state.value); }

    function asyncIncrement(clickId) {
      // Read current value
      const readValue = state.value;
      appendLog(logEl, `[click ${clickId}] read ${readValue}`);
      // Asynchronous delay simulating some async work
      setTimeout(() => {
        // Compute and write
        const newValue = readValue + 1;
        appendLog(logEl, `  [click ${clickId}] writing ${newValue}`);
        state.value = newValue; // write back
        render();
      }, randomDelay());
    }

    // Hook buttons
    let clickCounter = 0;
    document.getElementById('buggyInc').addEventListener('click', () => {
      clickCounter++;
      asyncIncrement(clickCounter);
    });

    // Rapid click helper: simulate many clicks over duration
    document.getElementById('buggyRapid').addEventListener('click', () => {
      const start = Date.now();
      const duration = 2000; // 2s
      const step = 100; // one click every 100ms
      const intervalId = setInterval(() => {
        if (Date.now() - start > duration) { clearInterval(intervalId); return; }
        clickCounter++;
        asyncIncrement(clickCounter);
      }, step);
    });

    // Initialize
    render();
    appendLog(logEl, 'Buggy counter initialized. Click repeatedly to see lost increments.');
  })();


  // ---- Fixed version ----
  (function(){
    let state = { value: 0 }; // separate shared state
    const valueEl = document.getElementById('fixedValue');
    const logEl = document.getElementById('fixedLog');
    function render() { valueEl.textContent = String(state.value); }

    // Simple async mutex that queues work and runs them serially.
    // Promise-based: acquire returns a release function (or use runExclusive helper)
    function createMutex() {
      let tail = Promise.resolve();
      return {
        // run an async function fn exclusively, in order
        runExclusive(fn) {
          const run = () => fn();
          // chain onto tail, but ensure downstream tasks wait for this to finish
          const result = tail.then(run, run);
          // update tail to wait for result completion
          tail = result.then(() => {}, () => {});
          return result;
        }
      };
    }

    const mutex = createMutex();

    function asyncIncrement(clickId) {
      // We want to serialize the entire read-modify-write section.
      // Wrap it in mutex.runExclusive so no two increments interleave.
      mutex.runExclusive(async () => {
        // Read current value inside the lock/queue
        const readValue = state.value;
        appendLog(logEl, `[click ${clickId}] read ${readValue}`);
        // Simulate asynchronous operation still (e.g., network, I/O)
        await new Promise(res => setTimeout(res, randomDelay()));
        const newValue = readValue + 1;
        appendLog(logEl, `  [click ${clickId}] writing ${newValue}`);
        state.value = newValue;
        render();
      });
    }

    // Hook buttons
    let clickCounter = 0;
    document.getElementById('fixedInc').addEventListener('click', () => {
      clickCounter++;
      asyncIncrement(clickCounter);
    });

    document.getElementById('fixedRapid').addEventListener('click', () => {
      const start = Date.now();
      const duration = 2000; // 2s
      const step = 100; // one click every 100ms
      const intervalId = setInterval(() => {
        if (Date.now() - start > duration) { clearInterval(intervalId); return; }
        clickCounter++;
        asyncIncrement(clickCounter);
      }, step);
    });

    // Initialize
    render();
    appendLog(logEl, 'Fixed counter initialized. Uses an async mutex to serialize updates.');
  })();

  // Also allow resetting both counters with R key
  window.addEventListener('keydown', (e) => {
    if (e.key === 'r' || e.key === 'R') {
      // naive reset by reloading page for a clean state
      location.reload();
    }
  });
  </script>
</body>
</html>

Explanation (concise and precise)

- What breaks in the buggy version:
  - Each click's handler reads the current shared state (state.value) and then schedules an asynchronous callback (setTimeout) to write back read+1.
  - Because setTimeout delays vary and JavaScript interleaves these callbacks with other events, two callbacks can both read the same original value before either writes. Example: state = 0; two clicks -> both read 0; both later write 1 -> net increase is 1 instead of 2. This is the classic read-modify-write race.
  - This is not due to threads in the OS; it's due to asynchronous callback interleaving and non-atomic update sequences.

- Why the fixed version works:
  - It serializes the entire read-modify-write sequence using an async mutex/queue (mutex.runExclusive). Each increment operation waits for previous ones to finish before reading and writing.
  - Even though each operation still performs async waits (setTimeout), they are executed one after another so no two operations read the same original value concurrently. That preserves correctness.

- Alternatives and notes:
  - Other fixes: use atomic update APIs (if available), update state deterministically from event data (e.g., increment a counter of pending clicks and fold), avoid read-modify-write by computing new value from previous writes only, or use functional updates (setState(prev => prev+1) pattern in React).
  - The mutex shown is simple and sufficient for demos. In real systems, minimize critical-section work to avoid latency magnification.

Run the demo: rapidly click "Increment" on both panels and watch the logs. On the buggy side you'll see multiple clicks reading the same value and later writing the same new value (lost increments). On the fixed side each click read/writes in sequence and no increments are lost.
